  "prompt": "How can you determine the derivative of [math]\\sin x^2[/math]?",
  "response": "To determine the derivative of the function \\( f(x) = \\sin(x^2) \\), we can use the chain rule from calculus. The chain rule states that if you have a composite function \\( f(g(x)) \\), then its derivative is given by:\n\n\\[\nf'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x)\n\\]\n\nIn our case, let \\( g(x) = x^2 \\) and \\( f(u) = \\sin u \\) (where \\( u = g(x) \\)). \n\n1. First, we need to compute the derivative of the outer function \\( f(u) = \\sin u \\):\n   \\[\n   f'(u) = \\cos u\n   \\]\n\n2. Next, we compute the derivative of the inner function \\( g(x) = x^2 \\):\n   \\[\n   g'(x) = 2x\n   \\]\n\n3. Now we apply the chain rule:\n   \\[\n   \\frac{d}{dx} [\\sin(x^2)] = f'(g(x)) \\cdot g'(x) = \\cos(x^2) \\cdot (2x)\n   \\]\n\nThus, the derivative of \\( \\sin(x^2) \\) is given by:\n\\[\n\\frac{d}{dx} [\\sin(x^2)] = 2x \\cos(x^2)\n\\]",
